display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{G}\in  Z(G)]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{G}g=g=g1_{G}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We also see for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in  Z(G)]]></fr:tex> and any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(xy)g=x(yg)=x(gy)=(xg)y=(gx)y=g(xy)]]></fr:tex> which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z(G)]]></fr:tex> is closed under multiplication.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We also see for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  Z(G)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  G]]></fr:tex> that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{-1}g=((x^{-1}g)^{-1})^{-1}=(g^{-1}x)^{-1}=(xg^{-1})^{-1}=gx^{-1}]]></fr:tex> which implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{-1}\in  Z(G)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z(G)]]></fr:tex> has a group structure induced from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
